<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920221-0042</DOCNO><DOCID>920221-0042.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Warnaco Group Inc.:   Firm Planning New Issue   To Help Reduce Its Debt</HL><DATE>02/21/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   WAC</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>CLOTHING AND FABRICS (CLO)STOCK AND BOND REGISTRATIONS, PRICINGS (REG)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)</IN><NS>BOND AND STOCK REGISTRATIONS AND PRICINGS (REG)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Warnaco Group Inc. once more is tapping the stock marketto pay debt.   The New York-based lingerie maker, which went public againin October after having been taken private in 1986, said itplans to issue five million more common shares. In addition,it said it has arranged a $350 million loan to refinance itshighrisk, high-yield &quot;junk&quot; bonds.</LP><TEXT>   Warnaco sold six million common shares to the public inOctober at $20 each. It used the proceeds to repay debt andrepurchase a portion of its preferred shares outstanding. Inlate composite trading yesterday on the New York StockExchange, Warnaco stock was quoted at $32.25, unchanged.   Warnaco has about $430 million remaining of the debt thecompany incurred in the 1986 management-led leveraged buy-outfor $550 million.   The company said that the refinancing would reduce theinterest rate on its debt to about 7% from 13% and wouldresult in annual interest savings of $28 million.</TEXT></DOC>